  <section class="bg-tjb-cream pt-16 pb-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
      <p class="eyebrow mb-4">Understanding Your Birth Team</p>
      <div class="w-10 h-0.5 bg-tjb-rose-500 mb-6"></div>
      <h1 class="text-[2.5rem] md:text-[3.25rem] font-bold mb-6 leading-[1.12]">Doula vs Midwife: What's the Difference?</h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-tjb-gray leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
        <strong>Doula vs midwife</strong> is one of the most Googled questions in pregnancy, and the confusion is completely understandable. Both words show up in birth plans. Both sound like they belong in the delivery room. But they are not the same thing at all. Here is the honest, clear breakdown so you can build the right team for your birth.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-16 bg-white">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 prose">

      <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
      <p>A <a href="/what-is-a-doula/" class="text-tjb-rose-500 hover:text-tjb-rose-600 transition"><strong>doula</strong></a> provides emotional, physical, and informational support. She is not a medical provider. She does not deliver babies, check your cervix, write prescriptions, or monitor fetal heart tones. She is your advocate, your comfort, your steady presence.</p>
      <p>A <strong>midwife</strong> is a medical provider. She can deliver your baby, write prescriptions, order labs, monitor your health, and manage complications within her scope. She is part of your clinical care team.</p>
      <p>And yes, you can have both. Many families do.</p>

      <h2>What a Doula Does</h2>
      <p>A doula stays with you throughout labor. She suggests positions, applies counter-pressure, offers encouragement, and helps you understand what is happening so you can make informed decisions. She supports your partner, too, so they know how to help rather than feeling helpless on the sidelines.</p>
      <p>There are three main types of doulas:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Birth doula:</strong> supports you during pregnancy and labor</li>
        <li><a href="/postpartum-doula/" class="text-tjb-rose-500 hover:text-tjb-rose-600 transition"><strong>Postpartum doula:</strong></a> helps you after the baby arrives with feeding, recovery, newborn care, and emotional support</li>
        <li><strong>Full-spectrum doula:</strong> supports all pregnancy outcomes, including loss, surrogacy, and adoption</li>
      </ul>
      <p>A doula does not replace your doctor or midwife. She does not perform any clinical tasks. Her job is to make sure you feel informed, supported, and heard. Learn more about <a href="/what-is-a-doula/" class="text-tjb-rose-500 hover:text-tjb-rose-600 transition">what a doula is</a> and the <a href="/benefits-of-a-doula/" class="text-tjb-rose-500 hover:text-tjb-rose-600 transition">evidence behind doula support</a>.</p>

      <h2>What a Midwife Does</h2>
      <p>A midwife is a trained healthcare provider who manages your prenatal care, attends your birth, and provides postpartum medical care. She can deliver your baby, suture tears, order blood work, prescribe medications, and refer you to a specialist if needed.</p>
      <p>There are three main types of midwives in the United States:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Certified Nurse Midwife (CNM):</strong> a registered nurse with a graduate degree in midwifery. CNMs can practice in all 50 states, work in hospitals and birth centers, and write prescriptions. This is the most common type of midwife in the U.S.</li>
        <li><strong>Certified Professional Midwife (CPM):</strong> trained specifically for out-of-hospital births (home and birth center). CPMs are licensed in some states but not all. They do not have a nursing background.</li>
        <li><strong>Direct-Entry Midwife (DEM):</strong> learned midwifery through apprenticeship or a non-nursing program rather than through nursing school. Licensing and scope vary widely by state.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The key distinction: a midwife has medical authority and clinical responsibility for you and your baby. A doula does not.</p>

      <h2>Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>

